Merseyside Fire & Rescue issued an update about an incident in Rainford, some 13miles away from Liverpool. Crew members from the UK's 12th largest fire service arrived at the scene in the early hours of the morning after they received a number of calls. Five fire engines have since arrived at the scene, with the earliest stationed at 12.53am. JUST IN: Trafalgar Square fire: Panic as smoke covers central London - emergency services at scene Firefighters arrived to find a large barn, which is estimated to be around 10 x 20 metres, had caught fire. According to Merseyside Fire & Rescue: "[They] acted quickly to secure water supplies and cool boundaries immediately." Crews tackled the blaze with main branch hoses. The brigade has also warned people should avoid the area and urged residents to keep doors and windows closed. DON'T MISS:Hated Brexit deal ‘could shatter UK’ [OPINION]Farage blasts those blaming conflict in Ukraine for inflation [NEWS]Britons blast Tories and Labour who are ‘as bad as each other’ [OPINION] They even suggested residents should keep medicines for any existing conditions nearby and said anyone facing ill effects should call NHS 111 for advice. The incident remains ongoing and is likely to continue throughout the night. 